Why AtomicInteger is Faster:
Lock-Free Mechanism:

AtomicInteger uses CAS (Compare-And-Swap), which avoids blocking threads.
Threads work independently until contention arises, making it more efficient.
Synchronized Overhead:

Synchronization involves acquiring and releasing a lock, which is slower because of context switching and potential thread contention.
Things to Note:
Performance may vary based on:

Number of threads.
System architecture (CPU cores, scheduling).
JVM optimizations.
Use Case Selection:

Use AtomicInteger when only atomic operations like incrementing are needed.
Use synchronized when you need more complex critical sections or logic.

